Paste this content ðŸ‘‡

ðŸ“„ git-commands.md
# Git Commands Reference

## Setup & Config
### git --version
Shows the installed Git version.
Example:
git --version

### git config --global user.name
Sets the Git username.
Example:
git config --global user.name "Akash Nimje"

### git config --global user.email
Sets the Git email address.
Example:
git config --global user.email "akash@example.com"

---

## Basic Workflow
### git init
Initializes a new Git repository.
Example:
git init

### git status
Shows the current state of the working directory and staging area.
Example:
git status

### git add
Adds files to the staging area.
Example:
git add git-commands.md

### git commit
Saves staged changes to the repository.
Example:
git commit -m "Add initial git commands reference"

---

## Viewing Changes
### git log
Shows commit history.
Example:
git log

### git diff
Shows differences between working directory and last commit.
Example:
git diff

### git log --oneline
Shows compact commit history.
Example:
git log --oneline


Save and exit.




âœ… Task 4: Stage and Commit
git add git-commands.md
git status


You should see:

Changes to be committed:
  new file: git-commands.md


Commit:

git commit -m "Add initial git commands reference"


View history:

git log





âœ… Task 5: Build Commit History (do this 3 times)

Edit file again:

nano git-commands.md


Add more commands (append this):

### git show
Shows details of a specific commit.
Example:
git show

### git rm
Removes file from Git and working directory.
Example:
git rm file.txt


Save â†’ then:

git diff
git add git-commands.md
git commit -m "Add more viewing and file commands"


Repeat once more by adding:

### git mv
Renames a file tracked by Git.
Example:
git mv old.txt new.txt


Commit:

git add git-commands.md
git commit -m "Add rename command example"

View compact history
git log --oneline


Example output:

a3f21c3 Add rename command example
b92d1fa Add more viewing and file commands
c31ab88 Add initial git commands reference





